Today I had to figure out a way to isolate 2 Voucher-based Transitional Housing providers in a report designed to show Average Length of Stay by provider. You run the report based on Program Type Code, so if you choose "Transitional Housing" in the prompts, I wanted the report to show whether each Transitional Housing project was classified as Voucher or Facility and give an average for each type. Nowhere in our HMIS is this distinction made as to whether the provider is Voucher based or Facility based with any kind of certainty, though I realize many implementations may have this question in their Provider assessment.
<!--more-->
Sure, in the bed data, there is a place to indicate whether the beds are Voucher or Facility, but this report was not looking at bed data, and I didn't want to have to pull those data elements in just for this. I also could have added a question to our Provider Assessment and populated it, but again, I chose to just handle this in the report itself instead. I may change my mind and go back to do it this way so that I can adjust that data in ServicePoint and my reports will dynamically adjust, but for now, this is the way I did it.

I created a variable called VoucherOrFacility that went like this:

=If(
[Leavers].[Entry Exit Provider Program Type Code]="Transitional housing (HUD)" And
(Match([Leavers].[Entry Exit Provider Id];"*(607)")=1 Or
Match([Leavers].[Entry Exit Provider Id];"*(91)")=1);
"V";
If(
Not([Leavers].[Entry Exit Provider Program Type Code]="Transitional housing (HUD)");
"N/A";
"F"))

This basically says that if you're running this report on Transitional Housing, then assign Providers 91 and 607 a "V", and assign everything else an "F". And if you're not running it on Transitional Housing, then assign it an "N/A".

If the literal Provider ID (meaning the number, not the name) was easily accessible in the Entry Exit Universe, I would have used that instead of Match, but because the Provider ID number is embedded into the Provider ID field with the name, I wanted to find a way of referring to these specific providers without having to type out their Provider names, which could change one day anyway.

So I used the Match function. It returns a 0 for False and a 1 for True. So if you are trying to find where an object contains a specific string, you can require that what is inside the Match parentheses is true by putting =1. Use * to indicate any or no characters precede or come after the string you are looking for. Use a ? for one wild card character.

Once I had the variable created, I added a column for "Vouchers or Facility?" then used Breaks on it to get the table to split so that each section could have its own Average. All I had to do to get the Averages was to select the "Average Length of Stay" column and click the Average function in the toolbar. No formula adjustments were necessary to account for V and F and N/A. In order to get the cell to the left of the Average to read correctly, I used this formula:

=If(
[VoucherOrFacility]="F";
"Facility Average";
If(
[VoucherOrFacility]="V";
"Voucher Average";
If(
[VoucherOrFacility]="N/A";
"Average")))

This way, if I run the report on a Program Type Code other than Transitional Housing, the label in front of the average will read correctly and there will be no breaking going on because the variable will return "N/A" on everything, and it will look like there are no shenanigans going on behind the scenes regarding V's or F's.

To bring this full circle, I decided that it while it was necessary to have the V or F column in the table, it wasn't necessary to see it, so I closed it up really tight so it just looks like a double lined border.

Definitely not saying this is the best way to handle isolating these two providers in my report, but it was fast and it works!

